{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609132"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:41:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:41:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16084"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16084"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0,0.61,0.1,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8775"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67280"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8775"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16084"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52732"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"295"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7033"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20958"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22526"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67280"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EEctopic pregnancy occurs when a fertilised ovum implants outside the uterine cavity. The most common site is the fallopian tube, accounting for approximately 95% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most serious complication that could occur?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fistula formation","Foetal malformation","Haemoperitoneum","Placental abruption","Pre-eclampsia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most serious complication of ectopic pregnancy is \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaemoperitoneum\u003C/strong\u003E, which occurs when the ectopic pregnancy ruptures through the fallopian tube wall causing internal bleeding. This is a medical emergency requiring immediate surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst there are increased risks of \u003Cstrong\u003Efoetal malformation\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Efistula formation\u003C/strong\u003E, these are not so acute or great a problem as rupture and haemoperitoneum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacental abruption\u003C/strong\u003E requires a normally-situated placenta within the uterus and \u003Cstrong\u003Epre-eclampsia\u003C/strong\u003E is a disorder of later pregnancy requiring a functioning placenta\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEctopic pregnancy typically presents between 6-10 weeks gestation with abdominal pain and vaginal bleeding. Rupture can cause cardiovascular collapse due to internal haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ectopic pregnancy most commonly occurs in the fallopian tube and can rupture causing life-threatening intraperitoneal hemorrhage.","Early recognition of ectopic pregnancy is crucial as it remains a leading cause of maternal mortality in the first trimester."],"references":["Sivalingam VN, Duncan WC, Kirk E, Shephard LA, Horne AW. Diagnosis and management of ectopic pregnancy. J Fam Plann Reprod Health Care. 2011 Oct;37(4):231-40. doi: 10.1136/jfprhc-2011-0073. Epub 2011 Jul 4. PMID: 21727242; PMCID: PMC3213855","Mullany K, Minneci M, Monjazeb R, C Coiado O. Overview of ectopic pregnancy diagnosis, management, and innovation. Womens Health (Lond). 2023 Jan-Dec;19:17455057231160349. doi: 10.1177/17455057231160349. PMID: 36999281; PMCID: PMC10071153","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52732"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16084"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52732"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T15:31:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T15:31:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8775"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67280"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/